# part 6: bash script and processes
Write a shell script that will keep running for 10 mins in the background and check the process that it's
created and try to kill using commands.

vim monitor_process.sh                     # edit script 
#!/bin/bash
# monitor_process.sh
sleep 600 &
PID=$!
echo "Started background process with PID: $PID"
# Run the script for 10 minutes
START_TIME=$(date +%s)
END_TIME=$((START_TIME + 600))

while [ $(date +%s) -lt $END_TIME ]; do
    if ps -p $PID > /dev/null; then
        echo "Process $PID is still running. Attempting to kill it..."
        kill -9 $PID && echo "Process $PID killed."
    else
        echo "Process $PID has already exited."
    fi
    sleep 10  # prevent CPU spike
done
echo "10 minutes are over. Script finished."
chmod +x monitor_process.sh                # make executable
./monitor_process.sh                       #run the script

notes:
ps → check if process exists
#!/bin/bash — run with Bash.
sleep 600 & — spawn a 10-minute background process; PID=$! saves its PID.
Compute END_TIME so the script itself runs for 600 seconds.
while loop runs until END_TIME, checking the child each iteration.
If child exists ps -p $PID, try kill -9 $PID and report; otherwise print it’s gone.
sleep 10 prevents a tight CPU loop.
After 10 minutes the loop exits and the script prints it’s finished.

